The point of Chisel is to facilitate meaningful crypto data 
transactions for various UTXO currencies. It has two basic
parts:

1. A proxy that can be run on a server which exposes a subset
of API commands, written in Python. (ravenProxy.py)
2. A vanilla Javascript library that interacts with the proxy
and also adds the local ability to sign messages with the 
elliptic library.

This changes the role of a core blockchain node to simply
pass data-rich transactions into the memory pool. I started
using it with the Digibyte blockchain, but found the ecosystem 
to be somewhat fragile because I needed to rely on certain sites
that had indexed the addresses.

With ravencoin, the core server includes address indexes and assets.

Chisel also includes other commands such as a javascript version of
"unspendable" which can figure out the last six digits of any 
unspendable crypto address.

